2D Arrays (Multi-Dimensional / Matrices) 🖼️
🧠 Logic:
2D Array ko Array of Arrays ya Matrix kehte hain. Ismein data rows (panktiyon) aur columns (stambhon) ke roop mein store hota hai. Access karne ke liye do indices: [row_index][col_index] ki zaroorat hoti hai.

📌 Example:

Java

// 2x3 matrix
int[][] matrix = {
    {1, 2, 3},
    {4, 5, 6}
};

// Accessing the element at Row 1, Column 2 (value 6)
System.out.println(matrix[1][2]); // 6
🔤 Java Code:
Java

public class TwoDArrayExample {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // 3x3 array initialization
        int[][] grid = new int[3][3];
        int value = 1;

        // Nested loop se values assign karna
        for (int i = 0; i < 3; i++) {
            for (int j = 0; j < 3; j++) {
                grid[i][j] = value++;
            }
        }

        // Nested loop se values print karna
        for (int i = 0; i < grid.length; i++) {
            for (int j = 0; j < grid[0].length; j++) {
                System.out.print(grid[i][j] + "\t");
            }
            System.out.println(); // Har row ke baad nayi line
        }
    }
}

/* Output:
1	2	3	
4	5	6	
7	8	9
*/
🧾 Notebook Points:
Java

📘 2D Array:
→ Matrix (Rows x Columns)
→ Requires two indices: [row][col]

🔢 Access: matrix[r][c]
✅ Summary Table:
🏷️ Array Type	⚙️ Dimension	🧮 Indices
1D Array	Single (Row)	arr[i]
2D Array	Multi (Row x Column)	matrix[i][j]
